8. Enforcement, Audit & Damages

  The enforcement mechanisms, audit rights, and damages provisions in this Section apply to any breach of Section 4. They do not apply to use that is not Commercial Use as defined in Section 2.

  Any breach of Section 4 automatically and immediately terminates this License unless cured within the following period after written notice from the copyright holder:

  (a) 90 days for entities with Group Annual Revenue below USD 1 million;
  (b) 30 days for entities with Group Annual Revenue between USD 1 million and USD 100 million;
  (c) Termination is immediate and permanent for entities with Group Annual Revenue exceeding USD 100 million, provided the 90-day grace period for a Threshold Crossing (as defined in Section 2) has already expired.
  
  Upon written notice specifying the alleged breach, the copyright holder may demand an independent audit no more than once per calendar year. The audit shall commence within 10 business days of notice. If a violation is found, the audited party bears all audit and legal costs.

  Damages:
  In the event of a breach of Section 4, the Commercial Software Entity shall be liable for damages calculated as follows:

  (i) For European Entities: Damages shall be equal to the greater of (a) three times a reasonable commercial royalty, or (b) a reasonable percentage of the revenue of the specific business unit or product line using the Software, not to exceed the limits of applicable law for liquidated damages.
  (ii) For all other Entities (Non-European): Damages shall be equal to the greater of (a) three times a reasonable commercial royalty, or (b) 10% of the entity’s Group Annual Revenue during the period of violation.

  For any calculation under this Section, there shall be a rebuttable presumption that the revenue attributable to the infringing use is no less than the aforementioned amounts, and the burden of proof to demonstrate a lower amount lies exclusively with the accused party.

  If any part of this calculation is determined by a court to be unenforceable as an excessive penalty, the damages shall be automatically reduced to the maximum amount permissible under applicable law.
  
